Description: Represents the date on which the estimated gestational age of pregnancy was determined.
Date of the first day of the last menstrual period.
The postpartum status of a patient. If the template is present, the patient is in the postpartum period.
The estimated due date (EDD) is the date that spontaneous onset of labor is expected to occur.
The date the pregnancy status was recorded.
Method used to determine whether a woman is pregnant or not, for example blood tests, urine tests, and ultrasound scans.

State or condition of being pregnant or intent to become pregnant.
Examples include but are not limited to pregnant, not pregnant, and unknown.

The estimated gestational age (in weeks, or weeks and fraction of week) of the pregnancy at the time of the health care encounter (in contrast to the gestational age at birth), beginning from the time of fertilization. Needs to be correlated with the date the gestational age was documented. Gestational age (written with both weeks and days) is calculated using the best obstetrical estimated delivery date (EDD) based on the following formula: Gestational Age = (280 - (EDD - Reference Date))/ 7.
Method for estimating gestational age, e.g., ultrasound, date of LMP.

Data Element Name: Estimated Date of Delivery Determination Method
Description: Method used to estimate the date of delivery, e.g., data from LMP, ultrasound etc.

A hazard that is specific to a person's work or work environment for a single job and with which the person might come in contact. A hazard is a source of potential harm to an individual's physical or mental health (e.g., biological, chemical, physical, psychological, radiological).
The self-reported Employer Address; this is not necessarily the work location.

The company, organization, or individual that provides compensation for a job or that assigns work to a volunteer, as reported by the person. For a military position, this is the self-reported duty station (home base).

A self-reported term that identifies the kind of business, i.e., primary business activity, in which a person has worked for the longest time while in their Usual Occupation. For a military position, this is the self-reported branch of service. If an appropriate term is not available (e.g., a new kind of business), then a text entry is used.

A self-reported, coded term for the type of work (paid or unpaid) done by a person for the longest amount of time during his or her life, not including voluntary work (done by choice for the benefit of others without compensation).
Date and timestamps associated with the completion of laboratory results, that are meta data associated with laboratory results.
An identifier for the analysis of specimens derived from humans which provide information for the diagnosis, prevention, treatment of disease, or assessment of health.
Additional Information: Data element included in the Electronic Reporting and Surveillance Distribution (eRSD) Reportable Condition Trigger Codes (RCTC)

Description: State or condition of a laboratory test.

Substance being sampled or tested.
Examples include but are not limited to nasopharyngeal swab, whole blood, serum, urine, and wound swab.
Analysis of specimens derived from humans which provide information for the diagnosis, prevention, treatment of disease, or assessment of health.
Additional Information: Data element included in the Electronic Reporting and Surveillance Distribution (eRSD) Reportable Condition Trigger Codes (RCTC)

Description: The clinically relevant date/time of the observation. In the case of observations taken directly from a subject, it is the actual date and time the observation was obtained. In the case of a specimen-associated study, this field shall represent the date and time the specimen was collected or obtained.

Sequence of characters assigned by a laboratory for an individual specimen.
Example includes but is not limited to accession number.
Documented findings of a tested specimen including structured and unstructured components.
Body location from where a specimen was obtained. Examples include but are not limited to right internal jugular, left arm, and right eye.
Identifier for the laboratory order from the encounter.
Date/time when clinical specimen was collected from subject patient.
The unique identifier assigned by the provider to reference a single patient.
Patient's nominated care provider.
The patient’s usual country of residence.
A person’s internal sense of being a man, woman, both, or neither.
Title of the currently held job.
Patient's self-identification as Hispanic/ Latino or Non- Hispanic/ Non-Latino.
Patient vital status of alive/dead.
Occupation which the subject currently holds.
Known or estimated year, month, and day of the patient's birth.
The patient's country of nationality.
Numbers or symbols to contact an individual with a  legal or familial relationship to a patient using a telephone.
Known or estimated year, month, and day of the patient's death.
Phone number of the current employer.
An individual’s response to the race question based upon self-identification.
Process of obtaining membership in a federally recognized tribe or tribal community
Documented language that the patient would like to use when discussing health care.
All names for the patient, including legal names and aliases. Must include the name type (i.e., legal or alias), first name, middle name, and last name.
Medicare Beneficiary Identifiers (MBI) used to uniquely identify Medicare patients.
An identifier for the patient.
Email address of the person with a legal or familial relationship to a patient.
Documentation of a specific instance of sex and/or gender information.
Type of business (industry) in which the subject currently holds a job.
Place where a person is located or may be contacted. Includes street name, number, city/town, state, and zip code.

All names for the patient’s parent or guardian, including legal names and aliases (if patient age is < 18 years).  May include name type (i.e., legal or alias), first name, middle name, and last name.

Currently consistently housed but experiencing any of the following circumstances in the last 12 months: behind on rent or mortgage, 3 or more relocations, housing cost burden, homelessness, or risk of eviction.

Shared housing includes a broad range of settings, such as apartments, condominiums, student or faculty housing, national and state park staff housing, transitional housing, and domestic violence and abuse shelters.
List of patient symptoms (structured) for the reportable event.
Place where a patient’s care is delivered.
Additional Information: USCDI+ Public Health: Data element included in the Electronic Reporting and Surveillance Distribution (eRSD) Reportable Condition Trigger Codes (RCTC)

Description: Current state of the encounter: Planned; Arrived; Triaged; In progress; On leave; Finished; Cancelled;Entered in error; Unknown.
Place or setting to which the patient left a hospital or encounter.
Additional Information: USCDI+ Public Health: Data element included in the Electronic Reporting and Surveillance Distribution (eRSD) Reportable Condition Trigger Codes (RCTC)

Description: Date and time the patient was admitted to a treatment facility; e.g., hospital
Category of health care service. Examples include but are not limited to office visit, telephone assessment, and home visit.
Coded diagnoses associated with an episode of care.
Reason the encounter takes place, expressed as a code.
Sequence of characters by which an encounter is known.

Assessments of a patient’s physical, cognitive, intellectual, or psychiatric disabilities.
Examples include but are not limited to- vision, hearing, memory, and activities of daily living.

State or condition of being pregnant or intent to become pregnant.
Examples include but are not limited to pregnant, not pregnant, and unknown.
The facility's fax number with area code.
Category describing available services or resources. Examples include but are not limited to laboratory, pharmacy, hospital, ambulatory providers, long-term and post-acute care, and pharmacy.
A collection of information used to give the location of a physical place of available services or resources.
Word or words by which a facility is known.
Sequence of characters representing an organization responsible for the provisioning and upkeep of the patient care location.
The facility's phone number with area code.
Sequence of characters representing a physical place of available services or resources.
The dates spent in a location traveled to.
A location in a person’s travel history either as an address or as a coded location.

Whether the direction of exposure/contact is acquisition (patient is the target and another person, animal, location, etc. is the source) or transmission (patient is the source and another person, animal, location, etc. is the target).
The date or period on which the possible exposure/contact occurred.
The type of exposure/contact (environmental, activity, event, location, person, animal, etc.) to an agent.
The possible agent of concern in the exposure/contact.

The source or target of the exposure or contact. Could be person, animal, or location. Either the patient's contact with an entity (person, animal, or substance) or presence at a location where exposure to an agent could have occurred or the patient's contact with an entity (person, animal, or substance) or presence at a location where transmission from the patient could have occurred.
Activity performed for or on a patient as part of the provision of care.
Additional Information: USCDI+ Public Health: Data element included in the Electronic Reporting and Surveillance Distribution (eRSD) Reportable Condition Trigger Codes (RCTC)

Description: Interventional, surgical, diagnostic, or therapeutic procedures or treatments planned as a result of the encounter.
The reason a procedure was performed.
Additional Information: Data element included in the Electronic Reporting and Surveillance Distribution (eRSD) Reportable Condition Trigger Codes (RCTC)

Description: The anatomical location qualifier where the procedure is performed. These include qualifiers for relative location, directionality, number, and plane, and exclude qualifiers for laterality.
Additional Information: Data element included in the Electronic Reporting and Surveillance Distribution (eRSD) Reportable Condition Trigger Codes (RCTC)

Description: The outcome of a procedure.
Additional Information: Data element included in the Electronic Reporting and Surveillance Distribution (eRSD) Reportable Condition Trigger Codes (RCTC)

Description: Whether or not the patient asserts they have verifiable vaccine credentials.
The date the vaccination event occurred.
Indicates the current status (i.e., completed, entered in error, not done) of the immunization event.
The code for the vaccine that was administered or was to be administered.

Suspected diagnoses or problems that represent that the patient may have a potentially reportable condition. For example, these may be diagnoses recorded in an EHR problem list and diagnosis codes used for billing for the encounter.
Additional Information: Data element included in the Electronic Reporting and Surveillance Distribution (eRSD) Reportable Condition Trigger Codes (RCTC)

Description: Date when a problem/ condition started.
List of patient symptoms (structured) for the reportable event.
Date of first determination by a qualified professional of the presence of a problem or condition affecting a patient.
The date on which the reporting party (e.g., physician, nurse practitioner, physician assistant, etc.), completes collection of minimum data for the eICR.
The date and time at which the EHR system sends the eICR data to the jurisdictional PHA or designee
A chronological description of the progression of the patient’s present illness from the first sign and symptom to the present.

A medical history includes an inquiry into the patient's medical history, past surgical history, family medical history, social history, allergies, and medications the patient is taking or may have recently stopped taking.
Review of Systems (ROS) is an inventory of body systems obtained by asking a series of questions to identify signs and/or symptoms the patient may be experiencing or has experienced.
A concise statement describing the reason for the encounter, usually stated in the patient’s own words.
State or condition of a laboratory test.

Sequence of characters assigned by a laboratory for an individual specimen.
Example includes but is not limited to accession number.

Substance being sampled or tested.
Examples include but are not limited to nasopharyngeal swab, whole blood, serum, urine, and wound swab.

Uniquely identifies the type of test (at minimum by using test name and manufacturer (similar to the make and model of a car)) that was used to obtain the Test Result Value. It is a device identifier and should be referenced using Device Identifiers (DI), when available. The DI is contained within the unique device identifier (UDI), created by manufacturer (Manufacturer requests UDI issuance, then provides DI, or can be pulled from GUDID database (https://accessgudid.nlm.nih.gov/).
An identifier for the analysis of specimens derived from humans which provide information for the diagnosis, prevention, treatment of disease, or assessment of health.
Additional Information: Data element included in the Electronic Reporting and Surveillance Distribution (eRSD) Reportable Condition Trigger Codes (RCTC)

Description: Information regarding a specimen, including the container, that does not meet a laboratory’s criteria for acceptability. Examples include but are not limited to hemolyzed, clotted, container leaking, and missing patient name. Usage note: This may include information about the contents of the container, the container, and the label.

Categorical assessment of a laboratory value, often in relation to a test's reference range.
Examples include but are not limited to high, low, critical high, and normal.
Date/time when clinical specimen was collected from subject patient.
Documented findings of a tested specimen including structured and unstructured components.

The clinically relevant date/time of the observation. In the case of observations taken directly from a subject, it is the actual date and time the observation was obtained. In the case of a specimen-associated study, this field shall represent the date and time the specimen was collected or obtained.
Date and timestamps associated with the completion of laboratory results, that are meta data associated with laboratory results.
Unit of measurement to report laboratory test results.

Upper and lower limit of quantitative test values expected for a designated population of individuals.
Usage note: Reference range values may differ by patient characteristics, laboratory test manufacturer, and laboratory test performer.
Body location from where a specimen was obtained. Examples include but are not limited to right internal jugular, left arm, and right eye.
The unique identifier for a single instance of a specimen received by a laboratory and its analysis.
The amount of the medication given at one administration event.
A code (or set of codes) that specify the medication that was administered.
The units of measure associated with the amount of medication prescribed. (e.g., milligrams, milliliters).
The date when the prescription was initially written or authored.
Represents a therapeutic response (as opposed to an undesired reaction) to the administration of a medication.
Indication that a medication should be taken by or given to the patient after being discharged from an encounter.
Reference to a condition that is the reason for the medication administration.
Indicates the amount of medication per dose that is to be used by the patient.
Description/ list of medications supplied to a patient with the intention that it is subsequently consumed by the patient.
The units of measure associated with the amount of medication given at one administration event.
Indicates who or what performed the medication administration and how they were involved.
A code (or set of codes) that specify this medication, or a textual description if no code is available.
A specific date/time or interval of time during which the administration took place (or did not take place, when the 'notGiven' attribute is true).
The information determined as a result of making the observation.
The provider's email address.
The first and last name of the provider.
The provider's phone number with area code.
The providers's fax number with area code.
The geographical location or mailing address of the provider's office or facility. Address must include street address, office or suite number (if applicable), city or town, state, and zip code.
Identification code for the care provider.
Date on which the pregnancy outcome occurred.
The result of the subject’s delivery, such as live birth or not a live birth.

Cause of death information includes the sequence of events leading to death as well as other conditions significantly contributing to death. The underlying cause of death may be different than the terminal condition. This may include summary of death note, and/or death information that may be captured within the discharge summary note or other cause of death documentation within the clinical notes section. Documented in Progress Notes if known. Documented in Death Certificate signed by physician (typically pcp, emergency doc, or coroner).
